{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17505713","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17505713"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:34:37+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:34:37+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2470"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2470","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2470"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.1,0.61,0.05,0.21,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2470"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52334"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2470","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2470"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2470"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"37672"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"43"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1036"},{"type":"tags","id":"2772"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4977"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"9735"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11626"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"},{"type":"tags","id":"11676"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2090"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2110"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3165"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8257"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8722"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14970"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42500"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52334","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/52334"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn 81-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with her son. Her son is concerned that over the last two weeks his mother has experienced intermittent episodes of dizziness and palpitations. She denies any fainting episodes. She has a medical history of hypertension, intermittent atrial fibrillation and a recent diagnosis of dementia. Her regular medications include perindopril, amlodipine, apixaban, and donepezil. Three weeks ago, she completed a course of ciprofloxacin for a chest infection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears tired. Her pulse rate is 50/min, blood pressure 128/65 mmHg, respiratory rate 14/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.4\u00b0C. Cardiorespiratory examination is normal. She has mild dependent oedema. Full blood count and serum electrolytes are unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate initial investigation to diagnose the underlying cause of the patient\u0027s presentation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Thyroid function tests","12-Lead ECG","Exercise stress test","Echocardiogram","Chest X-ray"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient\u0027s presentation is concerning for long QT syndrome, a potentially serious cardiac condition that can be acquired as a side effect of certain medications, including quinolone antibiotics such as ciprofloxacin. The most appropriate investigation to diagnose this condition is a \u003Cstrong\u003E12-Lead ECG\u003C/strong\u003E. Long QT syndrome is characterized by a prolongation of the QT interval on ECG, which can lead to symptoms such as palpitations, dizziness, and syncope. The patient\u0027s recent symptoms, along with the timing of her ciprofloxacin course, strongly suggest this diagnosis. An ECG would directly visualize any QT interval prolongation, making it the most appropriate first-line investigation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThyroid function tests\u003C/strong\u003E could be considered to rule out thyroid-related fatigue, but there are no specific symptoms suggesting thyroid dysfunction in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn \u003Cstrong\u003Eexercise stress test\u003C/strong\u003E can be useful in diagnosing long QT syndrome, especially in cases where the QT interval is normal at rest. However, it would not be the first-line investigation if the pathology could be initially detected on a resting ECG.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn \u003Cstrong\u003Eechocardiogram\u003C/strong\u003E would not show signs of long QT syndrome. It would be more useful if there was clinical suspicion of heart failure or structural heart disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Echest X-ray\u003C/strong\u003E would be appropriate for diagnosing conditions like pulmonary oedema or ongoing lung infection. However, this patient shows no signs of these conditions, and her previous chest infection has been treated.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn summary, given the patient\u0027s symptoms and recent medication history, a 12-lead ECG is the most appropriate initial investigation to diagnose the suspected long QT syndrome. If confirmed, management would involve discontinuing the offending medication (in this case, ciprofloxacin has already been stopped) and monitoring for resolution of symptoms and ECG changes.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Ciprofloxacin and other quinolone antibiotics may cause acquired long QT syndrome.","Long QT syndrome is best diagnosed with a 12-lead ECG.","Symptoms of long QT syndrome include palpitations, dizziness, and syncope."],"references":["Prabhakar M, Krahn AD. Ciprofloxacin-induced acquired long QT syndrome. Heart Rhythm. 2004 Nov 1;1(5):624\u20136. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/15851230/","Wilde AAM, Amin AS, Postema PG. Diagnosis, management and therapeutic strategies for congenital long QT syndrome. Heart. 2022 Mar;108(5):332-338. Available at: https://heart.bmj.com/content/early/2021/05/26/heartjnl-2020-318259"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"37672"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2470"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"37672","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/37672"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-09-03T20:35:02+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-03T20:36:15+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2470"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52334"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"43","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/43"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc8a","name":"Pharmacology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"4"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"cre